 tales of women and snakes converging in a representation of territorial claims and noble status. These works reveal that the qualities traditionally used to define sovereignty—lineage and gender among them—are in fact mobile and contingent. In medieval literary texts, as McCracken demonstrates, human dominion over animals is a disputed model for sovereign relations among people: it justifies exploitation even as it mandates protection and care, and it depends on reiterations of human-animal difference that paradoxically expose the tenuous nature of human exceptionalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnimalsxSymbolic aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aHides and skins in literature. 0aHides and skinsxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aHides and skinsxSymbolic aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistory. 0aSovereignty in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aFrance.  aanimality.  adomestication.  adominion.  agender.  amedieval literature.  aprotection.  asovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022645892240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226459080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226459080/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles